'''Aaron Belisarius Cosmo Sibthorpe''' (183?–1916) was a nineteenth century [[African people|African]] historian. He published both ''History and Geography of Sierra Leone'' in 1868.

Sibthorpe was born somewhere near [[Benin]], and after being captured and enslaved, he became a [[Liberated Africans in Sierra Leone|Liberated African]] in [[colonial Sierra Leone]] while still a youth. He remained in Sierra Leone all his life. He became a school teacher, teaching in villages around [[Freetown]].<ref name="July">{{cite book|last1=July|first1=Robert W.|title=Origins of Modern African Thought|date=2004|publisher=Africa World Press|location=Trenton}}</ref>{{rp|263}}

He became a prominent member of the [[Sierra Leone Creole people|Krio]] community. However, by the time of his death he had been forgotten.<ref name="Cromwell">{{cite book|last1=Cromwell|first1=Adelaide M|title=An African Victorian Feminist The Life and Times of Adelaide Smith Casely Hayford 1848-1960.|date=1986|publisher=Frank Cass|location=London}}</ref>

