'''James Davidson''' is a professor of [[ancient history]] at the [[University of Warwick]]. Davidson specialises in the [[social history]] of [[ancient Greece]] and has made significant contributions to the study of ancient [[homosexuality]]. He was educated at [[Columbia University| Columbia]] and [[Oxford University]], where he received a [[DPhil]].<ref>https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/staff/jamesdavidson/ [[Warwick University]], 24 October 2017. Retrieved 3 May 2018 </ref> From 2001 to 2004 he was a member of the Council for the [[Society for the Promotion of Hellenic Studies]] from 2001 to 2004, and from 2000 to 2010 a member of the [[Classical Association]] Journals Board.<ref name=warwick>{{cite web|url=https://www2.warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/staff/jamesdavidson/|publisher=www2.warwick.ac.uk|title=Professor James Davidson – University of Warwick|accessdate=2017-04-14}}</ref> His book ''The Greeks and Greek Love: a Radical Reappraisal of Homosexuality in Ancient Greece'' was awarded the [[Mark Lynton History Prize]] in 2010. <ref>https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/staff/jamesdavidson/publications/ [[Warwick University]] 14 March 2014. Retrieved 3 May 2018.</ref>

